  "prompt": "What are Some interesting facts of Langar at golden temple?",
  "response": "Langar, the community kitchen at the Golden Temple (Harmandir Sahib) in Amritsar, is one of the most remarkable aspects of Sikh hospitality and service. Here are some interesting facts about Langar at the Golden Temple:\n\n1. **Historical Roots**: The concept of Langar was instituted by Guru Nanak Dev Ji, the founder of Sikhism, and was further expanded by the third Guru, Guru Amar Das Ji. It was designed to promote equality and selfless service.\n\n2. **Free Meals for All**: Langar provides free meals to anyone, regardless of their background, religion, caste, or creed. This embodies the Sikh principle of equality and serves as a practical expression of the faith's teachings.\n\n3. **Vegetarian Menu**: All meals served in Langar are vegetarian, adhering to the principles of non-violence and compassion towards animals.\n\n4. **Daily Servings**: The Langar at the Golden Temple serves around 50,000 to 100,000 people each day, and during special occasions and festivals, this number can exceed 150,000.\n\n5. **Selfless Service (Seva)**: The preparation and serving of Langar are conducted by volunteers, known as \"sewadars,\" who dedicate their time and effort to this selfless act of service. People from all walks of life come together to work in the kitchen.\n\n6. **Simple and Nutritious food**: The typical Langar meal includes dal (lentils), sabzi (vegetable curry), roti (unleavened bread), rice, and sometimes sweet dishes like kheer (rice pudding). The food is wholesome, nutritious, and cooked in large quantities.\n\n7. **Kitchen Scale**: The community kitchen at the Golden Temple is one of the largest in the world. It is equipped with massive cooking vessels and infrastructure to handle the significant volume of food prepared daily.\n\n8. **Operational Round the Clock**: Langar operates continuously throughout the day, ensuring that anyone who arrives can be served a meal, no matter the time.\n\n9. **Sense of Community**: Eating together in Langar fosters a sense of community and fellowship, breaking down barriers and promoting harmony among diverse groups.\n\n10. **Global Inspiration**: The model of Langar has inspired similar initiatives worldwide, promoting communal meals as a practice of inclusion, charity, and social responsibility.\n\n11. **Inclusivity**: Everyone can participate, including tourists and those who are not Sikh. Visitors are encouraged to sit on the floor together and share a meal, reflecting the core values of the Sikh faith.\n\n12. **Efficient Operations**: Modern techniques are used to prepare the vast amounts of food, including industrial-sized cooking equipment, yet the essence of traditional cooking is preserved.\n\nThe Langar at the Golden Temple is not just about feeding the hungry; it is an educational experience that embodies the spirit of community service, equality, and compassion central to Sikh philosophy.",
